type="local"
href="nst-002J.xml"
addr="nst-002J"
title="Proof by contradiction">Proof by contradiction</fr:link>.) Assume <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p'(x)\neq 0]]></fr:tex>. Then
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[p(x)=p'(x)q(x)+r(x),]]></fr:tex>
where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\deg (r)<\deg (p')]]></fr:tex> by the division algorithm.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Now assume for contradiction <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p(x)]]></fr:tex> has a double root <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha ]]></fr:tex>, then
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[r(\alpha )=p(\alpha )-p'(\alpha )q(\alpha )=0.]]></fr:tex>
Then the minimal polynomial divides the remainder polynomial <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m_{\alpha }(x)\mathrel {\bigm |} r(x)]]></fr:tex>, so that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m_{\alpha }(x)\neq  p(x)]]></fr:tex> and so <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p(x)]]></fr:tex> is reducible. This contradicts the hypothesis that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p(x)]]></fr:tex> is irreducible. Hence the result.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:tree
